revision.text:
[[File:Armenian Genocide survivors map.png|thumb|Armenian Genocide survivors map]] '''Armenian Genocide survivors''' are [[Western Armenia]]ns who were not killed in the [[Armenian Genocide|Genocide of 1915]]. Most of the survivors became [[refugee]]s outside Turkey, the [[successor state]] of the Ottoman Empire.
About 70,000 Armenians [[Armenians in Turkey|remain in Turkey]], mostly in Istanbul. This figure does not include an unknown number of [[cultural assimilation|assimilated]] [[Crypto-Armenians]].
== Distribution == [[File:US State Department document on Armenian Refugess in 1921.jpg|thumb|The US State Department document of the Armenian population in 1921.]]
According to the [[US State Department]], in 1922 there were 817,873 Armenian refugees who had originated from Turkey.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/6/66/US_State_Department_document_on_Armenian_Refugess_in_1921.jpg|title=Approximate number of Armenian in the world, November 1922|publisher=}}</ref> This figure was based upon information provided by the British Embassy in Constantinople and 1921 data from the Near East Relief Society. The total given did not include able-bodied Armenians detained by Kemalist Turkey, nor Armenian women and children - approximately 95,000, according to the League of Nations – who have been forced to convert to Islam.
According to the same source, there were 281,000 Armenians still living in Turkey in 1921: 150,000 in Constantinople (Istanbul) and 131,000 in Asia Minor.
===Eastern Armenia=== {{see also|Democratic Republic of Armenia#Refugee problem}} There was also an Armenian settlement problem that brought conflict with other ethnic residents. In all, there were over 300,000 embittered and impatient Armenian refugees escaping from the Ottoman Empire which were now the [[Democratic Republic of Armenia|DRA]] government's responsibility. This proved an insurmountable humanitarian issue. Typhus was a major sickness, because of its effect on children. Conditions in the outlying regions, not necessarily consisting of refugees, weren't any better. The Ottoman governing structure and Russian army had already withdrawn from the region. The Armenian government had neither time nor resources to rebuild the infrastructure. The 393,700 refugees were under their jurisdiction as follows:{{Citation needed|date=February 2011}}
{| class="wikitable" |- ! '''Districts''' ! '''Number of refugees''' |- | [[Yerevan]] | 75,000 |- | [[Ejmiatsin]] | 70,000 |- | [[Gavar|Novo-Bayazit]] (Gavar) | 38,000 |- | [[Vayots Dzor|Daralagyaz]] (Vayots Dzor) | 36,000 |- | [[Aparan|Bash-Abaran]] (Aparan) | 35,000 |- | [[Ashtarak]] | 30,000 |- | Akhta - Yelenovka (Hrazdan - Sevan) | 22,000 |- | [[Garni|Bash-Garni]] (Garni) | 15,000 |- | [[Vanadzor|Karakilisa]] | 16,000 |- | [[Dilijan]] | 13,000 |- ! '''Armenia''' ! '''350,000''' |} The government of [[Hovhannes Kachaznuni]] was faced with a most sobering reality in the winter of 1918-19. The newly formed government was responsible for over half a million Armenian refugees in the Caucasus. It was a long and harsh winter.<ref>{{cite book | last =Hovannisian | first =Richard G. | title =The Republic of Armenia: The First Year, 1918-1919, Vol. I | publisher = University of California Press | year =1971 | location =Berkeley | isbn =0-520-01984-9 | pages =126–155}}</ref> The homeless masses, lacking food, clothing and medicine, had to endure the elements. Many who survived the exposure and famine succumbed to the ravaging diseases. By the spring of 1919, the typhus epidemic had run its course, the weather improved and the first [[American Committee for Relief in the Near East]] shipment of wheat reached Batum. The British army transported the aid to Yerevan. Yet by that time some 150,000 of the refugees had perished. Vratsian puts this figure at around 180,000, or nearly 20% of the entire nascent Republic. A report{{By whom|date=February 2011}} in early 1919 noted that 65% of the population of Sardarabad, 40% of the population of eight villages near Etchmiadzin and 25% of the population of Ashtarak had died.{{Citation needed|date=February 2011}}
