{{For|those of a similar name|Constantin David (disambiguation)|David Constantine}} {{Infobox person | name = David Constantin | image = <!-- just the filename, without the File: or Image: prefix or enclosing [[brackets]] --> | alt = | caption = | birth_name = | birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1974|07|26|df=y}} | birth_place = [[Mauritius]] | death_date = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} or {{Death-date and age|Month DD, YYYY|Month DD, YYYY}} (death date then birth date) --> | death_place = | nationality = [[Mauritian]] | other_names = | known_for = ''[[Les Accords de Bella]]'' | occupation = Filmmaker }} '''David Constantin''' (born 1974) is a filmmaker from [[Mauritius]].
==Career==
Constantin was born in Mauritius Island in 1974. He obtained a degree in Information and Communication, and then attended the ESAV (Higher School of Audiovisuals) in Toulouse.<ref name=mubi/> He made his first short film in 1998.<ref name=COE/> After spending five years in France studying cinematography he returned to Mauritius in 2003. In 2007 he organized ILE COURTS, the first short film festival in Mauritius.<ref name=mubi/> David Constantin has established an audiovisual research laboratory at the Charles Baudelaire Cultural Centre. He gives introductory courses for teachers on analysis of the image.<ref name=COE/> He has given seminars on aspects of film for the [[Université populaire de l'Ile Maurice]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.upim.info/intervenants/david-constantin/ |title=David Constantin |publisher=Université populaire de l'Ile Maurice |accessdate=2012-03-11}}</ref>
==Work==
In 2002 Constantin directed and produced the short film ''[[Diego l'interdite]]'' (Diego the Forbidden). This is a documentary about the deportation of the people of the [[Chagos Island]] in the Indian Ocean by the US and UK governments.<ref name=mubi/> The film won the European Grand Prix of First Films 2002 and Vues d'Afrique 2003.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fcat.es/FCAT/index.php?option=com_zoo&task=item&item_id=248&Itemid=37 |title=Diego l'interdite |work=FCAT |accessdate=2012-03-11}}</ref> In the years that followed he directed and produced a number of documentaries and short films. He won awards in film festivals such as Vues d’Afrique (Montreal), Amiens (France), Réunion and Milan.<ref name=mubi/> His 2005 short ''Bisanville (l'Autobus)'' won prizes at the International Film Festival of Amiens in 2005 and the 12th Film Festival of Africa and the Islands, Reunion 2005.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.africultures.com/php/index.php?nav=film&no=5796 |title=BISANVIL (L'AUTOBUS) |work=Africultures |accessdate=2012-03-11}}</ref> His short comedy ''[[Made In Mauritius]]'' was screened at the 2010 [[African Film Festival of Cordoba]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fcat.es/FCAT/index.php?option=com_zoo&task=item&item_id=430&Itemid=37 |title=Made in Mauritius |work=FCAT |accessdate=2012-03-11}}</ref> It was also screened at the 22nd African, Asian and Latin American Film Festival in Milan in March 2012.<ref name=COE/>
