{{Infobox person | honorific_prefix = | name = Sean Saifa Wall | honorific_suffix = | image = <!-- filename only, no "File:" or "Image:" prefix, and no enclosing [[brackets]] --> | image_size = | alt = | caption = | native_name = | native_name_lang = | pronunciation = | birth_name = <!-- only use if different from name above --> | birth_date = <!-- {{birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} for living people supply only the year unless the exact date is already widely published, as per [[WP:DOB]] --> | birth_place = | residence = [[Atlanta, Georgia]] | nationality = [[Americans|American]] | other_names = | ethnicity = <!-- Ethnicity should be supported with a citation from a reliable source --> | citizenship = | education = | alma_mater = [[Williams College]] | occupation = Intersex activist and researcher | years_active = | era = | employer = | organization = | known_for = Intersex and HIV advocacy | notable_works = <!-- produces label "Notable work"; may be overridden by |credits=, which produces label "Notable credit(s)"; or by |works=, which produces label "Works" --> | style = | home_town = [[The Bronx, New York]] | television = | spouse = <!-- Use article title or common name --> | partner = <!-- (unmarried long-term partner) --> | children = | parents = | relatives = | callsign = | awards = | website = {{URL|saifaemerges.com}}<!-- {{URL|example.com}} --> | footnotes = }}
'''Sean Saifa Wall''' is a black [[intersex]] man, advocate for [[intersex human rights|intersex rights]] and former president of [[Interact Advocates for Intersex Youth]].<ref name="niib">{{Cite journal| volume = 5| issue = 2| pages = 117–119| last = Wall| first = Sean Saifa| title = Standing at the Intersections: Navigating Life as a Black Intersex Man| journal = [[Narrative Inquiry in Bioethics]] | date = 2015| url = http://muse.jhu.edu/journals/nib/summary/v005/5.2.wall.html}}</ref><ref name="adv">{{cite web|last1=Wall | first1 = Sean Saifa |last2=Davis | first2 = Georgiann | authorlink2 = Georgiann Davis | title=Op-ed: Hey, Fox News, Intersex Is Not A Punchline |url=http://www.advocate.com/commentary/2014/02/26/op-ed-hey-fox-news-intersex-not-punchline |website=[[The Advocate (LGBT magazine)|The Advocate]]|accessdate=August 29, 2016 |date = February 26, 2014}}</ref> He is widely published, and works in intersex and HIV advocacy, and social documentary.
{{external media | width = 210px | align = right | headerimage= | video1 = [https://www.buzzfeed.com/lizzwarner/what-its-like-to-be-intersex " What It’s Like To Be Intersex"], Lizz Warner, [[BuzzFeed]]}}
==Early life and career==
Sean Saifa Wall has described growing up in the Bronx in the 1980s a family with other intersex members. In an interview by [[Pidgeon Pagonis]], he describes how an uncle of his was forced to sleep outside on the porch of his hospital after a surgery, and how his intersex and black identities are inseparable.<ref name="ef-jun3-2016">{{cite web|first = Pidgeon |last = Pagonis | authorlink = Pidgeon Pagonis|title=6 Things Intersex Folks Need to Know About How We Perpetuate Anti-Black Racism|url=http://everydayfeminism.com/2016/06/intersex-anti-black-racism/|website=[[Everyday Feminism]]|accessdate=January 8, 2017|date=June 3, 2016}}</ref> Drawing parallels, Wall has stated, "Although seemingly different subjects, they share the same common denominator, state-sponsored violence against marginalized individuals".<ref name="wall2016" /> Diagnosed with [[partial androgen insensitivity syndrome]], he was subjected to a gonadectomy at age 13, necessitating lifelong hormone replacement therapy.<ref name="wall2016">{{Cite web| last = Wall| first = Sean Saifa| title = Love, complexity and inter-sectionality| work = [[Intersex Day]]| accessdate = 2017-01-19| date = November 8, 2016 | url = http://intersexday.org/en/love-complexity-intersectionality/}}</ref>
Wall volunteered for [[Gay Men's Health Crisis]] at age 14, prior to studying at [[Williams College]]. He later travelled to Cuba with [[Interreligious Foundation for Community Organization|Pastors for Peace]], documenting the local health system.<ref name="about">{{cite web|title = About Sean Saifa Wall | url = http://saifaemerges.com/saifa/ | work = EMERGE | accessdate = 2016-08-29}}</ref>
==Activism== Wall served as president of [[Interact Advocates for Intersex Youth]] for three years.<ref name="about" /> During that time, Interact filed a lawsuit, ''M.C. v. Medical University of South Carolina'', in the County of Richmond, South Carolina, in partnership with the [[Southern Poverty Law Center]].<ref>{{Cite| last = Southern Poverty Law Center| title = Groundbreaking SPLC lawsuit accuses South Carolina, doctors and hospitals of unnecessary surgery on infant| work = [[Southern Poverty Law Center]] | date = 2013-05-14| url = http://www.splcenter.org/get-informed/news/groundbreaking-splc-lawsuit-accuses-south-carolina-doctors-and-hospitals-of-unnece}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://interactadvocates.org/turning-the-lens-inward-sean-saifa-wall/ | title = Turning the Lens Inward: Sean Saifa Wall | date = October 15, 2014 | accessdate = 2016-08-29 | work = [[Interact Advocates for Intersex Youth]]}}</ref>
In 2015, Wall joined an international advisory board for a first philanthropic Intersex Human Rights Fund established by the [[Astraea Lesbian Foundation for Justice]].<ref name="astraea">{{cite web |url=http://www.astraeafoundation.org/news/344/60/Introducing-the-Intersex-Fund-team-at-Astraea |title=Introducing the Intersex Fund team at Astraea! |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=June 16, 2015 |website=[[Astraea Lesbian Foundation for Justice]] |publisher=Astraea Lesbian Foundation for Justice |access-date=2015-07-02 |quote= |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150703205803/http://www.astraeafoundation.org/news/344/60/Introducing-the-Intersex-Fund-team-at-Astraea |archivedate=July 3, 2015 |df= }}</ref> He has also developed an art project entitled EMERGE.<ref name="about" />
As part of his advocacy work, Wall has been interviewed by [[Nightline]], in a segment where he also confronted his childhood surgeon,<ref>{{Cite web| last = Murray| first = Ross| title = Intersex advocates correct and clarify Nightline news report| work = [[GLAAD]]| date = March 11, 2015| url = http://www.glaad.org/blog/intersex-advocates-correct-and-clarify-nightline-news-report}}</ref> [[BuzzFeed]],<ref>{{cite web | title = What It's Like To Be Intersex | url = https://www.buzzfeed.com/lizzwarner/what-its-like-to-be-intersex | work = [[BuzzFeed]] | date = March 29, 2015 | accessdate = 2016-08-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = https://mic.com/articles/113990/this-video-explains-what-it-s-like-and-what-it-isn-t-like-to-be-intersex#.3wHqubP3p | title = This Video Explains What It's Like — And What It Isn't Like — To Be Intersex | work = [[Mic (media company)|Mic.com]] | date = March 30, 2015 | accessdate = 2016-08-29}}</ref> HuffPost Live,<ref>{{cite web | last = Bolles | first = Alexandra | work = [[GLAAD]] | url = http://www.glaad.org/blog/video-intersex-advocates-talk-stigma-health-care-family-support-huffpost-live | title = VIDEO: Intersex advocates talk stigma, health care, & family support on HuffPost Live | date = April 22, 2014 | accessdate = 2016-08-29}}</ref> and written for [[The Advocate (LGBT magazine)|The Advocate]]<ref name="adv" /> and [[Quartz (publication)|Quartz]].<ref>{{Cite web| last1 = Wall| first1 = Sean Saifa| title = American surgeons are still mutilating children who don't look "normal"| work = [[Quartz (publication)|Quartz]]| accessdate = 2016-08-29| date = April 26, 2015 | url = http://qz.com/391209/american-surgeons-are-still-mutilating-children-who-dont-look-normal/}}</ref> Wall spoke at TEDxGrandRapids in May 2015.<ref>{{cite web| url = https://www.ted.com/tedx/events/15007 | title = Theme: Constant / Change | work = TEDxGrandRapids | accessdate = 2016-08-29}}</ref>
